olk, England"},"en":{"–before 16 January 1447":"–before 16 January 1447","–1447":"–1447","–1442":"–1442","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1362–Male":"1362–Deceased","1367–Female":"1367–Deceased","1384":"1384","1362":"1362","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1447":"1447","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1367":"1367","1453":"1453","1442":"1442","after 1442":"after 1442","before 16 January 1447":"before 16 January 1447","1328":"1328","Bordeaux, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France":"Bordeaux, Seine-et-Marne, France","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","United Kingdom":"United Kingdom","Buckenham Parva, Norfolk, England":"Buckenham Parva, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clifton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the very numerous places called Clifton, from Old English <i>clif</i> ‘slope’ (see   Cliff  ) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Cliff","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called Cliff(e), Cle(e)ve, or Clive, from Old English <i>clif</i> ‘slope, bank, cliff’, or a topographic name from the same word. The Old English word was used not only in the sense of modern English <i>cliff</i> but also of much gentler slopes and frequently also of a riverbank or seashore."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":0,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":9,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":54,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Clifton was born in Buckenham Parva, Norfolk, England as the son of Adam De Clifton and Margery. He had at least 1 daughter with Alice. He died before 16 January 1447, in Bordeaux, Seine-et-Marne, France."},"et":{"–before 16 January 1447":"–enne 16. jaanuari 1447","–1447":"–1447","–1442":"–1442","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1362–Male":"1362–Surnud","1367–Female":"1367–Surnud","1384":"1384","1362":"1362","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1447":"1447","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1367":"1367","1453":"1453","1442":"1442","after 1442"